<paragraph id="8B9F36E39616FF35FF9FFB2EFD44FA2B" blockId="52.[125,1172,1221,1501]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B129616FF35FF9FFB2EFE75FB2B" author="Ananthakrishnan TN" box="[125,411,1221,1245]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" pagination="113 - 138" refId="ref32428" refString="Ananthakrishnan TN. 1967. Studies on new and little known Indian Thysanoptera. Oriental Insects 1: 113 - 138." type="journal article" year="1967">Ananthakrishnan (1967)</bibRefCitation>
proposed a sub-genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FD4AFB2EFCC1FB2B" authorityName="Ananthakrishnan" authorityYear="1968" box="[680,815,1221,1245]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Saucrothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FD4AFB2EFCC1FB2B" box="[680,815,1221,1245]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Saucrothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for a single species from 
<collectingCountry id="F33776739616FF35FBBAFB2EFB7AFB2B" box="[1112,1172,1221,1245]" name="India" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">India</collectingCountry>
with antennal segment III very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FD87FB0EFD59FB0B" authorityName="Mound &amp; Minaei" authorityYear="2007" box="[613,695,1253,1277]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barrowi">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FD87FB0EFD59FB0B" box="[613,695,1253,1277]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">barrowi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, these two are not likely to be closely related, because the Indian species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FD97FAEEFD0DFAEB" authorityName="Ananthakrishnan" authorityYear="1967" box="[629,739,1285,1309]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Saucrothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scitulus">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FD97FAEEFD0DFAEB" box="[629,739,1285,1309]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">S. scitulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has the typical tooth-like tubercle at the inner apex of the fore tibiae that is found in many 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FCE2FACEFC25FACB" box="[768,971,1317,1341]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FCE2FACEFC9FFACB" box="[768,881,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Podothrips</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
from around the world. In contrast, all members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FDA6FAADFD51FAAB" authorityName="Ritchie" authorityYear="1974" box="[580,703,1349,1373]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FDA6FAADFD51FAAB" box="[580,703,1349,1373]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group discussed here lack this tubercle, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FF53FA8DFECAFA8B" authorityName="Mound &amp; Minaei" authorityYear="2007" box="[177,292,1381,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barrowi">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FF53FA8DFECAFA8B" box="[177,292,1381,1405]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. barrowi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably an Australian endemic derived from within this group. It is the only species discussed here that has the metathoracic sternopleural sutures developed, apart from 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FEE7FA4DFE6CFA4B" authorityName="Ritchie" authorityYear="1974" box="[261,386,1445,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FEE7FA4DFE6CFA4B" box="[261,386,1445,1469]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FE20FA4DFDADFA4B" baseAuthorityName="Kruger" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[450,579,1445,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasseni">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FE20FA4DFDADFA4B" box="[450,579,1445,1469]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">P. lucasseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike so many of the species in this genus, the apical antennal segments are brown not yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F36E39616FF35FE35F9EBFCBBF9EE" blockId="52.[125,853,1536,1593]" box="[471,853,1536,1560]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FE35F9EBFCBBF9EE" authority="(Kruger)" baseAuthorityName="Kruger" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[471,853,1536,1560]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasseni">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FE35F9EBFD0BF9EE" bold="true" box="[471,741,1536,1560]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Podothrips lucasseni</emphasis>
(Krüger)
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33A65689616FF34FF9FF9CAFE26FEF7" lastPageId="53" lastPageNumber="2971" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B9F36E39616FF35FF9FF9CAFDB0F9CF" blockId="52.[125,853,1536,1593]" box="[125,606,1569,1593]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">
<treatmentCitationGroup id="AB3011CD9616FF35FF9FF9CAFDB0F9CF" box="[125,606,1569,1593]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">
<treatmentCitation id="0A8110F29616FF35FF9FF9CAFDB4F9CF" author="Kruger W" box="[125,602,1569,1593]" page="105" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" year="1890">
<taxonomicName id="4C204D609616FF35FF9FF9CAFDB4F9CF" authority="Kruger 1890, p 105" authorityName="Kruger" authorityPageNumber="105" authorityYear="1890" box="[125,602,1569,1593]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Phloeothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasseni">
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FF9FF9CAFE89F9CF" box="[125,359,1569,1593]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Phloeothrips lucasseni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B129616FF35FE92F9CAFDE7F9CF" author="Kruger W" box="[368,521,1569,1593]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" pagination="105 - 106" refId="ref33366" refString="Kruger W. 1890. Ueber Krankheiten und Feinde des Zuckerrohrs. Berichte des Versuchstation fur Zuckerrohr in West-Java 1: 105 - 106." type="journal article" year="1890">Krüger 1890</bibRefCitation>
, p 105
</taxonomicName>
</treatmentCitation>
.
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F36E39616FF34FF9FF9B6FE26FEF7" blockId="52.[125,1172,1629,1685]" lastBlockId="53.[138,1185,137,257]" lastPageId="53" lastPageNumber="2971" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">
This is a widespread Asian species that is sometimes associated with sugar cane or even rice. It is recorded by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B129616FF35FE6EF996FDD6F963" author="Ritchie JM" box="[396,568,1661,1685]" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970" pagination="261 - 282" refId="ref34477" refString="Ritchie JM. 1974. A revision of the grass-living genus Podothrips (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae). Journal of Entomology B 43: 261 - 282." type="journal article" year="1974">Ritchie (1974)</bibRefCitation>
from Hawaii to 
<collectingCountry id="F33776739616FF35FCE6F996FC62F963" box="[772,908,1661,1685]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
, with both 
<emphasis id="B954EAF19616FF35FBFAF996FB7DF963" box="[1048,1171,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="2970">hawaiiensis</emphasis>
Moulton and 
<emphasis id="B954EAF19617FF34FED7FF62FE92FF56" box="[309,380,137,160]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="2971">oryzae</emphasis>
Priesner placed as synonyms. It differs from all of the Australian species in this genus in the character states indicated in the key (
<figureCitation id="131B2A669617FF34FC8DFF42FC0CFF37" box="[879,994,169,193]" captionStart="Figures 59–65" captionStartId="17.[138,207,1609,1628]" captionTargetBox="[138,1185,794,1573]" captionTargetId="figure-223@17.[138,1186,794,1573]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figures 59–65. (59) Haplothrips victoriensis, head and pronotum. (60) H. victoriensis, pelta. (61) Podothrips ardis, head and pronotum. (62) P. australis, head and pronotum. (63) P. australis, prosternites. (64) P. lucasseni, fore tibia. (65) P. barrowi, head and pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5233666" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5233666/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="2971">Figure 64</figureCitation>
), and also in the uniform brown body and femora contrasting with the yellow tibiae. Two small females have been studied from Darwin.
</paragraph>
